  <!-- ORIGIN STORY -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-label">Origin story</div>
    <div class="section-title">What went wrong — and why it matters</div>
    <div class="callout">
      <p>
        The original tutorial used MS SQL Server. Replicating it in MySQL Workbench produced a <strong>join explosion</strong> — row counts multiplied across every join in a way the tutorial never addressed. Rather than switching tools to match the tutorial, the root cause was diagnosed: the staging layer had no deduplication, so duplicate rows were being multiplied by every subsequent join. Fixing it properly meant <strong>rebuilding the pipeline from the ground up</strong> using real analytics engineering practices. That decision turned a guided tutorial into an independent engineering project.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ENGINEERING DECISIONS -->
  <section class="section" id="decisions">
    <div class="section-label">Engineering decisions</div>
    <div class="section-title">Why each choice was made</div>
    <ul class="decisions">
      <li>
        <span class="dec-key">ETL job log</span>
        <span class="dec-val">Every pipeline run records start time, end time, row count, and status. A team can monitor pipeline health <strong>without reading code</strong> — which is the standard in any remote data team.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="dec-key">Unknown sentinels</span>
        <span class="dec-val">Each dimension table has an "unknown" record at id=1. Foreign keys fall back to this instead of NULL, <strong>preserving referential integrity</strong> even when source data is incomplete.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="dec-key">Non-destructive dedup</span>
        <span class="dec-val">ROW_NUMBER() over the full business key partition keeps the latest record and discards duplicates <strong>without deleting anything</strong> — the complete audit trail stays in staging.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="dec-key">DQ as a layer</span>
        <span class="dec-val">The quality report is persisted as a table, not just run and discarded. Quality metrics are <strong>queryable and comparable across pipeline runs</strong>.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="dec-key">Composite indexes</span>
        <span class="dec-val">Indexes on date_id, restaurant_id, and category_id together <strong>support common analytical query patterns</strong> without over-indexing every possible column.</span>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

